'''David Richardson''' (born April 25, 1957) is an American [[politician]] and [[certified public accountant]]. He is a [[Democratic Party of Florida|Democratic Party]] member of the [[Florida House of Representatives]]. He was elected on November 6, 2012, and represents the 113th district which is entirely within [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]] and contains the city of Miami Beach, as well as parts of downtown [[Miami]], [[Little Havana]], and [[North Bay Village]].

==Early life and career==
Richardson, who moved to Florida at age 10, graduated from [[Lyman High School]] in [[Longwood, Florida]] before attending the [[University of Central Florida]] in [[Orlando]], where he earned both a [[Bachelor of Science]] and a [[Bachelor of Science in Business Administration]]. He later earned an [[MBA]] from the [[University of Tampa]], studying at nights and weekends while working at [[The Pentagon]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidforflorida.com/page/about-david |title=About David |publisher=David Richardson for State Representative |date=2012-06-14 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>

After a stint as a public high school teacher in Orlando, Richardson embarked on a career as an accountant, working first for the [[Defense Contract Audit Agency]], an agency of the [[U.S. Department of Defense]]. He later joined [[Ernst & Young]] before establishing his own business in 1993. For seven years, he also taught part-time at the [[University of Maryland]], serving as an adjunct professor.<ref name=bio />

==Political career==
In February 2012, state Rep. [[Richard L. Steinberg]] (D<U+2013>Miami Beach) resigned following an investigation into inappropriate text messages he allegedly sent to a federal prosecutor.<ref name="miamiherald1">{{cite news|last=Smiley |first=David |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/02/29/2667996/florida-rep-steinbergs-resignation.html |title=Florida Rep. Steinberg<U+2019>s resignation could shake up Miami Beach City Hall |work=[[The Miami Herald]] |date=2012-02-29 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> His resignation created an open seat that attracted the interest of numerous local politicians.<ref name="miamiherald1"/> After several candidates withdrew,<ref>{{cite news|last=Smiley |first=David |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/05/17/2804452/miami-beach-commissioners-swap.html |title=Miami Beach commissioners swap interest in state House District 113 |work=[[The Miami Herald]] |date=2012-05-17 |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref> four Democrats were left in the race, with no Republicans or independents having filed.

In the Democratic primary held on August 14, 2012, Richardson won 33% of the vote, with his opponents garnering 27%, 24% and 16% respectively.<ref name=primary>{{cite news|work=[[The Miami Herald]] |url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/gaysouthflorida/2012/08/ahead-with-33-percent-david-richardson-poised-to-become-floridas-first-openly-gay-legislator.html |title=David Richardson of Miami Beach wins House race, becomes Florida's first openly gay legislator |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>  Richardson therefore secured the Democratic nomination. No Republican filed for the seat in the solidly Democratic district and Richardson ran unopposed in the November general election.<ref name="typepad1">{{cite news|work=[[The Miami Herald]] |url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/gaysouthflorida/2012/08/equality-florida-richardson-may-be-joined-in-house-by-gay-colleagues-joe-saunders-ian-whitney.html |title=Equality Florida: Richardson may be joined in House by gay colleagues Joe Saunders, Ian Whitney |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>

==Personal==
Richardson is openly [[gay]].<ref name=primary /> He took office on November 20, 2012, becoming the first openly gay member of the [[Florida Legislature]], a distinction he shared with [[Joe Saunders (Florida politician)|Rep. Joe Saunders]] (D<U+2013>Orlando), who is also a UCF alumnus.

Richardson's campaign won the support of the [[Gay & Lesbian Victory Fund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victoryfund.org/endorsed_candidates/profile/candidate:698 |title=Dave Richardson |publisher=The Gay & Lesbian Victory Fund |date= |accessdate=2012-08-15}}</ref>

